{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492321"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1033"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1033"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.02,0.06,0.79,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41962"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1033"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26951"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4853"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"882"},{"type":"contributions","id":"905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41962"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the GP with a two-year history of progressive hearing loss. It affects both ears and she finds it most difficulty with telephone conversations. She has no pain, discharge or dizziness. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes. She takes simvastatin, aspirin, perindopril and metformin daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination both ear canals and tympanic membranes are normal. Rinne\u0027s test is positive bilaterally and her Weber\u0027s test localises to the midline. Audiometry confirms bilateral, symmetrical sensorineural loss, most pronounced at high frequencies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Otosclerosis","Autoimmune middle ear disease","Aspirin ototoxicity","Presbycusis","Cholesteatoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history, examination and investigations in this stem are most consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Epresbycusis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is also known as age related hearing loss that occurs gradually, it affects over 40% of people aged over 70 years old. It results in sensorineural hearing loss at higher pitched sounds as suggested by the results of this patients investigations as well as difficulty on the telephone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E results in bilateral conductive hearing loss and most commonly presents in younger patients. \u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune middle ear disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare rapidly progressive condition. \u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin ototoxicity\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to occur at low doses and generally results in tinnitus rather than hearing loss. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholesteatoma\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly associated with unilateral conductive hearing loss and present with otalgia, discharging ear, and keratin debris/pus/polyps are seen on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rinne\u0027s test is positive when air conduction is louder than bone conduction in that ear (normal result)","Weber\u0027s test can detect unilateral conductive (lateralises towards the affected ear) or sensorineural hearing loss (lateralises away from the affected ear) but false positive results are high"],"references":["Chang, P \u0026 Kim, S. Cholesteatoma - diagnosing the unsafe ear (Internet). Australian Family Physician, Vol. 37; No. 8; August 2008. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2008/200808/200808chang.pdf","National Institute on Deafness and Other Communication Disorders (NIDCD). Age-related hearing loss (Internet). NIDCD Information Clearinghouse; 2018. Available at: https://www.nidcd.nih.gov/health/age-related-hearing-loss","Chang, P \u0026 Pedler, K. Ear Examination: A practical guide (Internet). Australian Family Physician, Vol. 34; No. 10; October 2005. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2005/200510/200510chang.pdf","Bell-Lehmkuhler, B. Autoimmune Inner Ear Disease (Internet). ASHA: American Speech-Language-Hearing Association. 2006. Available at: https://www.asha.org/Articles/Autoimmune-Inner-Ear-Disease/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26951"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1033"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26951"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-28T17:00:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-28T17:00:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1033"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41962"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t